h3. Problem Definition
When you click on user profile then "Recently viewed", it opens in a pop-up.
Opening "Recently worked on" menu from user profile should be consistent with opening "Recently viewed", in a popup and not in the dashboard.

h3. Suggested Solution
Implement a pop-up for "Recently worked on" when opening from user profile 
 
h3. Workaround
You can find the menu from user profile if needed by adding the following code in *Confluence Admin* > *Custom HTML* and insert the code in the *At end of the HEAD* :
{code:borderStyle=solid}
<script type="text/javascript">
    AJS.toInit(function(){
      AJS.$('#user-recently-worked-on').hide();
    });
</script>
{code}

More details can be found in [How to hide elements in Confluence using CSS or JavaScript|https://confluence.atlassian.com/confkb/how-to-hide-elements-in-confluence-using-css-or-javascript-313458894.html]

h3. Summary

When deleting a user in LDAP, and then renaming another user to that deleted user causes duplicates in {{user_mapping}} with the second having a {{null}} value for {{lower_username}}.
h3. Environment
 * Confluence 6.7.2
 * External LDAP

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Set up a fresh Confluence 6.7.2
 # Set up an external LDAP directory
 # Connect the external LDAP directory to Confluence as a User Directory
 # Create a user *tony_stark*
 # Create a user *ext_tony_stark*
 # Synchronise Confluence with external LDAP directory
 # Log in as *ext_tony_stark* and log out again (this sets up data like the People Directory)
 # Delete user *tony_stark* in LDAP
 # Rename *ext_tony_stark* to *tony_stark* in LDAP
 # Synchronise with external LDAP directory

h3. Expected Results

There should be only one entry in {{user_mapping}} for user each user.
{code:java}
confluence-6.7.2=> select * from user_mapping where username in ('tony_stark', 'ext_tony_stark');
             user_key             | username | lower_username 
----------------------------------+----------+----------------
 ff80808161f8b7b40161f8d1a60c0006 | tony_stark    | tony_stark
 ff80808161f8b7b40161f8d1a60b0005 | ext_tony_stark    | ext_tony_stark
(2 rows)
{code}
h3. Actual Results

There are 2 rows in {{user_mapping}} for {{username}} {{tony_stark}}, with {{null}} for the second.
{code:java}
confluence-6.7.2=> select * from user_mapping where username in ('tony_stark', 'ext_tony_stark');
             user_key             | username | lower_username 
----------------------------------+----------+----------------
 ff80808161f8b7b40161f8d1a60c0006 | tony_stark    | tony_stark
 ff80808161f8b7b40161f8d1a60b0005 | tony_stark    | 
(2 rows)
{code}
h3. Notes

Is caused by this code where it falls through to the second {{else if}} branch.
{code:java|title=com.atlassian.confluence.user.persistence.dao.hibernate.HibernateConfluenceUserDao}
  private void updateLowerName(ConfluenceUserImpl user, String newUsername, boolean overrideExisting) {
        ConfluenceUserImpl existingUser = (ConfluenceUserImpl) findByUsername(newUsername);
        if (existingUser == null) {
            user.setLowerName(IdentifierUtils.toLowerCase(newUsername));
        } else if (overrideExisting) {
            existingUser.setLowerName(null);
            getHibernateTemplate().update(existingUser);
            // Flush required because in a collection of pending session updates Hibernate doesn't guarantee that the
            // nulling of lowerName happens before the user name is re-used for 'user'
            getHibernateTemplate().flush();
            user.setLowerName(IdentifierUtils.toLowerCase(newUsername));
        } else {
            user.setLowerName(null);
        }
    }
{code}
h3. Workaround

At this time the workaround requires database manipulation to either update or remove the extra entry in {{user_mapping}}. Follow the steps in CONFSERVER-36018 for the workaround if users have logged in or the following steps do not work.
{panel:title=IMPORTANT|borderStyle=dashed|borderColor=#cccccc|titleBGColor=#f7d6c1|bgColor=#ffffce}
(!) Always back up your data before performing any modifications to the database. If possible, test any alter, insert, update, or delete SQL commands on a staging server first.
{panel}
You can check the data in the database with these queries.
{code:sql}
select * from user_mapping where username in (select username from user_mapping where lower_username is null);

select * from CONTENT inner join user_mapping on CONTENT.USERNAME = user_mapping.user_key where user_mapping.lower_username is null;

select count(*), CONTENT.CONTENTTYPE, user_mapping.username from CONTENT
inner join user_mapping on CONTENT.USERNAME = user_mapping.user_key where user_mapping.lower_username is null group by CONTENT.CONTENTTYPE, user_mapping.username
order by count(*) desc;
{code}
If the last query returns anything other than {{CONTENTTYPE = USERINFO}}, then follow the steps in Option 2.
h3. Option 1

*Please contact Atlassian Support if you are unsure about taking these steps as they are very specific to this bug report and cannot be applied generically.*
 # Turn on SQL Logging in  !https://confluence.atlassian.com/doc/files/590259974/590058056/1/1398739558493/Cog.png! > General Configuration > Logging and Profiling
 # Run this command in a terminal shell (adjust for location of atlassian-confluence.log)
{code:java}
tail -F /var/atlassian/application-data/confluence/logs/atlassian-confluence.log | fgrep -B 3 -i "[engine.jdbc.spi.SqlExceptionHelper] logExceptions Violation of UNIQUE KEY constraint 'unq_lwr_username'. Cannot insert duplicate key in object 'dbo.user_mapping'. The duplicate key value is (<NULL>)."
{code}

 # Run a full User Directory Sync and watch for output on the terminal
 # When you see something like (it will be for a different user)
{code:java}
2018-03-23 03:20:06,309 DEBUG [Caesium-1-2] [org.hibernate.SQL] logStatement update user_mapping set username=?, lower_username=? where user_key=?
2018-03-23 03:20:06,309 TRACE [Caesium-1-2] [type.descriptor.sql.BasicBinder] bind binding parameter [1] as [VARCHAR] - [tony_stark]
2018-03-23 03:20:06,310 TRACE [Caesium-1-2] [type.descriptor.sql.BasicBinder] bind binding parameter [2] as [VARCHAR] - [null]
2018-03-23 03:20:06,324 ERROR [Caesium-1-2] [engine.jdbc.spi.SqlExceptionHelper] logExceptions Violation of UNIQUE KEY constraint 'unq_lwr_username'. Cannot insert duplicate key in object 'dbo.user_mapping'. The duplicate key value is (<NULL>).
{code}
take note of the username listed in the 2nd line, here in the example is *tony_stark*.

 # Shutdown Confluence
 # Run these SQL delete commands to remove all the invalid user entries
{code:sql}
delete from logininfo where username in (select user_key from user_mapping where lower_username is null);
delete from notifications where username in (select user_key from user_mapping where lower_username is null);
delete from CONTENT where USERNAME in (select user_key from user_mapping where lower_username is null);
delete from content_label where owner in (select user_key from user_mapping where lower_username is null);
delete from label where owner in (select user_key from user_mapping where lower_username is null);
delete from user_mapping where lower_username is null;
{code}

 # Restart Confluence
 # Repeat these steps until there are no more errors

h3. Option 2

This involves changing the incorrect username in {{user_mapping}} to something that won't every sync again, and so will map all the content to an invalid user. As they do not have an entry in {{cwd_user}} they will not appear in searches or @ mentions.
 # Shutdown Confluence
 # Identify the broken user with
{code:sql}
select * from user_mapping where username in (select username from user_mapping where lower_username is null);
{code}

 # For the user with the {{null}} value for {{lower_username}} we update that with (here, we're using the example of *tony_stark* from above
{code:sql}
update user_mapping set username = 'tony_stark_donotuse', lower_username = 'tony_stark_donotuse' where user_key = (select user_key from user_mapping where username = 'tony_stark' and lower_username is null);
{code}
 

 # Restart Confluence

h3. Summary

In Confluence 6.7.x we introduced a new look and feel. If we navigate to a page and click on the elipsis (. . .) then attachments, we will see the attachments page. In this page we added icons/text to certain type of files. For the ppt/pptx, there is a typo in the span class.
{code:java}
<span class="iaui-icon content-type-attachment-powerpoint97" title="Microsoft Powerpoint 97 Slideshow">Microsoft Powerpoint 97 Slideshow</span>

{code}
There is an extra " i ". It should be " aui " instead of " iaui ". The correct class should be:
{code:java}
<span class="aui-icon content-type-attachment-powerpoint97" title="Microsoft Powerpoint 97 Slideshow">Microsoft Powerpoint 97 Slideshow</span>

{code}
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Install Confluence 6.7.x
 # Create a page
 # Add different file types, including ppt/pptx
 # Navigate to the Attachments page (...)

h3. Expected Results

No UI problem as per the screenshot with the fixed span class:
 !image-2018-03-05-12-06-51-221.png|thumbnail!
h3. Actual Results

The image icons, under Name, should hide the text that defines the file type and because of the typo in the span class, it is not hidden and it shows up as per the screenshot:
 !Screen Shot 2018-03-05 at 11.39.06 AM.png|thumbnail!

h3. Temporary workaround
{code:css}
/* Workaround for https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-55112 */
.iaui-icon {
    background-repeat: no-repeat;
    background-position: 0 0;
    border: none;
    display: inline-block;
    height: 16px;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    text-align: left;
    text-indent: -999em;
    vertical-align: text-bottom;
    width: 16px;
}
{code}

h4. Issue details
Certain log messages in catalina.out are logged with a relative timestamp instead of an absolute timestamp, for example:
{code}
3158102674 [Caesium-1-1] INFO com.atlassian.confluence.extra.officeconnector.index.excel.ExcelXMLTextExtractor - Not enough memory to extract all text from 'test.xlsx'. The attachment will be partially searchable.
{code}
{code}
3804257300 [http-nio-8090-exec-218] WARN com.benryan.webwork.WordImportAction - Failed to delete uploaded file /var/atlassian/application-data/confluence/temp/upload_98eca3a3_d34a_4c55_9c84_ad4dfefaecec_00001432.tmp
{code}

The first value represents milliseconds since confluence has been started. This violates all good rules about logging in that entries should be timestamped with a wall clock based time value so that entries can be searched or parsed into larger log management systems.

h5. Preferred results
Preferably, the log pattern should be similar to other messages in catalina.out, for example:
{code:borderStyle=solid}
01-Mar-2018 22:36:36.848 INFO [main] org.apache.coyote.AbstractProtocol.stop Stopping ProtocolHandler ["http-nio-8092"]
{code}

h4. The logging pattern
The log format is the [TTCC Layout|https://logging.apache.org/log4j/1.2/apidocs/org/apache/log4j/TTCCLayout.html], which is one of the standard log4j formats. In particular, [RelativeTimeDateFormat|https://logging.apache.org/log4j/1.2/apidocs/org/apache/log4j/helpers/RelativeTimeDateFormat.html] is used for the timestamp.

h4. Possible workarounds
In a test environment, add these lines to {{<confluence-install>/conf/logging.properties}} :
{code:borderStyle=solid}
### Catalina.out extended logging - place under section entitled "Handler specific properties" ###

1catalina.java.util.logging.SimpleFormatter.format=[%1$td.%1$tm.%1$tY %1$tH:%1$tM:%1$tS,%1$tL] %4$s [%2$s] %5$s %6$s %n

2localhost.java.util.logging.SimpleFormatter.format=[%1$td.%1$tm.%1$tY %1$tH:%1$tM:%1$tS,%1$tL] %4$s [%2$s] %5$s %6$s %n
{code}

h4. Next Steps
After implementing the above change, a restart of Confluence will be required for the change to take effect.

